    {
      "id": "b2h4c_vs_al2znse4_spinel",
      "type": "ged",
      "description": "B2H4C (carborane B/C cluster compound, B-B + B-H + B-C + C-H covalent bonds, 56 atoms) vs Al2ZnSe4_mp-1104860 (spinel polymorph, 14 atoms, Al(CN=6) octahedra + Zn(CN=4) tetrahedra + Se anions).  Originally discovered as a false positive in the 200-material clustering \u2014 the role-swap fired because B2H4C had inconsistent role labels (B='neutral', C='anion', H='cation') from pymatgen's composition_guess fallback, while Al2ZnSe4's clean cation/anion split let the matcher find a cohort-averaged near-zero alignment.  Fixed via the 'composition_guess_inconsistent_neutralised' rule in the v4 graph builder (`_determine_ion_roles`): when composition_guess produces a mix of neutral and ionic atoms in the same compound, all atoms get re-labelled neutral, which prevents the role-swap from finding a target alignment.  Test asserts non-trivial cost across all four lenses to enforce that the fix stays in place.",
      "graph_a": "B2H4C_mp-29655",
      "graph_b": "Al2ZnSe4_mp-1104860",
      "cif_a": "B2H4C_mp-29655.cif",
      "cif_b": "Al2ZnSe4_mp-1104860.cif",
      "assertions": [
        {
          "assert": "cost",
          "description": "Carborane cluster vs spinel \u2014 topology cost must reflect the topology mismatch.  Bound: at least 1.0 (well above clustering threshold of 0.1).  Pre-fix this scored 0.0.",
          "op": "ge",
          "value": 1.0
        },
        {
          "assert": "cost",
          "description": "Cost should remain bounded (relaxed to arbitrary high bound)",
          "op": "le",
          "value": 100
        },
        {
          "assert": "cost_polyhedral",
          "description": "Polyhedral lens: carborane clusters have face-sharing icosahedra; spinel has corner+edge octahedra",
          "op": "ge",
          "value": 1.0
        },
        {
          "assert": "cost_bond_length",
          "description": "Bond lengths differ by ~2\u00d7 (B-H ~1.1 \u00c5 vs Al-Se ~2.5 \u00c5)",
          "op": "ge",
          "value": 1.0
        }
      ],
      "tags": [
        "core"
      ],
      "optimizer": "v1",
      "cost_function": "v1"
    },
    {
      "id": "baal2te4_vs_mgal2o4_spinel",
      "type": "ged",
      "description": "BaAl2Te4 (P4/nbm tetragonal layered structure with Ba at 8-coordinate sites + Al at tetrahedral sites + Te bridging) vs MgAl2O4 (Fd-3m canonical normal spinel).  Discovered as a false positive in the 200-material 214-stoichiometry clustering: BaAl2Te4 is in Family 2 alongside genuine spinels.  The mapping is Ba(CN=8)\u2192Al(CN=6), Al(CN=4)\u2192Mg(CN=4) and Al(CN=4)\u2192Al(CN=6) [cross-CN fallback], Te\u2192O.  TopologyCost gives 0.0 because the cohort averaging across cross-CN matches: cohort A's mix of Ba(8 bonds) and Al(4 bonds) averages to 6 per cohort member, accidentally matching Al(spinel)'s CN=6.  The shell-walk rule's NN admissions absorb the per-key surpluses (cohort wants more O bonds, spinel has more O atoms in next-shell NN).  Bond-length, bond-angle, and polyhedral lenses all flag the mismatch (Ba CN=8 in tetragonal layers \u2260 spinel's 3D framework).  Test asserts non-trivial cost; **expected to FAIL until a deeper cohort-validation fix lands** (this test is an aspirational regression-direction guard).",
      "graph_a": "Ba(AlTe2)2_mp-28505",
      "graph_b": "MgAl2O4_mp-3536",
      "cif_a": "Ba(AlTe2)2_mp-28505.cif",
      "cif_b": "MgAl2O4_mp-3536.cif",
      "assertions": [
        {
          "assert": "cost",
          "description": "Tetragonal layered Ba(8)+Al(4) vs cubic spinel Al(6)+Mg(4) \u2014 must charge real topological mismatch (currently fails: cost=0)",
          "op": "ge",
          "value": 0.5
        },
        {
          "assert": "cost",
          "description": "Bounded",
          "op": "le",
          "value": 100
        },
        {
          "assert": "cost_polyhedral",
          "description": "Polyhedral lens correctly catches: layered tetragonal vs corner+edge spinel framework",
          "op": "ge",
          "value": 1.0
        },
        {
          "assert": "cost_bond_length",
          "description": "Al-Te (~2.7 \u00c5) vs Mg/Al-O (~1.9-2.0 \u00c5) \u2014 large length deviation",
          "op": "ge",
          "value": 1.0
        }
      ],
      "tags": [
        "core"
      ],
      "optimizer": "v1",
      "cost_function": "v1"
    },
    {
      "id": "capt2o4_vs_mgal2o4_spinel",
      "type": "ged",
      "description": "CaPt2O4 (P4_2/mmc tetragonal with Ca at 8-coordinate sites + Pt in square-planar coordination) vs MgAl2O4 spinel.  This is the most striking false positive in Family 2 \u2014 CaPt2O4 doesn't even have spinel-compatible cation CNs (Ca CN=8 vs spinel A-site CN=4 or B-site CN=6; Pt is 4-coordinate but in SQUARE-PLANAR geometry, fundamentally different from tetrahedral or octahedral).  The structure is essentially layered/intercalation-like.  Despite being 'pretty far off from a spinel' on inspection, the algorithm finds a cohort-consistent zero-cost alignment via cross-CN fallback: Ca(CN=8)\u2192Al(CN=6), Pt distributed as Pt\u2192Mg and Pt\u2192Al.  TopologyCost gives 0.0 because cohort averaging (8+4)/2=6 accidentally matches spinel's CN=6 for B-site.  All non-topology lenses correctly flag the mismatch.  **Expected to FAIL** as a regression-direction guard.",
      "graph_a": "Ca(PtO2)2_mp-558172",
      "graph_b": "MgAl2O4_mp-3536",
      "cif_a": "Ca(PtO2)2_mp-558172.cif",
      "cif_b": "MgAl2O4_mp-3536.cif",
      "assertions": [
        {
          "assert": "cost",
          "description": "Square-planar Pt + Ca CN=8 layered vs cubic spinel \u2014 must charge (currently fails: cost=0)",
          "op": "ge",
          "value": 0.5
        },
        {
          "assert": "cost",
          "description": "Bounded",
          "op": "le",
          "value": 100
        },
        {
          "assert": "cost_polyhedral",
          "description": "Polyhedral lens: layered Pt squares vs spinel octahedra+tetrahedra",
          "op": "ge",
          "value": 1.0
        }
      ],
      "tags": [
        "core"
      ],
      "optimizer": "v1",
      "cost_function": "v1"
    },
    {
      "id": "becr2o4_chrysoberyl_vs_mgal2o4_spinel",
      "type": "ged",
      "description": "BeCr2O4 (Pnma \u2014 chrysoberyl/olivine-derived, isolated BeO4 tetrahedra in HCP-O sublattice + edge-sharing CrO6 octahedra) vs MgAl2O4 (Fd-3m spinel \u2014 corner+edge-sharing octahedra in CCP-O sublattice + tetrahedra).  Same first-shell histograms (Be CN=4=Mg CN=4, Cr CN=6=Al CN=6, O CN=4=O CN=4) but fundamentally different framework topology.  This is a textbook instance of the Mg2SiO4 vs MgAl2O4 failure mode applied to the spinel/olivine pair.  All cation-anion bond counts match per atom; cohort comparison gives perfect equality with no surplus/deficit; TopologyCost gives 0.0 by construction.  Polyhedral connectivity is the distinguishing signal (BeCr2O4 is purely corner-sharing for its tetrahedra; MgAl2O4 has edge-sharing octahedra).  **Expected to FAIL** under TopologyCost; addressing it requires either second-shell features in TopologyCost or moving the unsupervised clustering to a WeightedSum that includes PolyhedralCost.",
      "graph_a": "BeCr2O4_mp-1193887",
      "graph_b": "MgAl2O4_mp-3536",
      "cif_a": "BeCr2O4_mp-1193887.cif",
      "cif_b": "MgAl2O4_mp-3536.cif",
      "assertions": [
        {
          "assert": "cost",
          "description": "Chrysoberyl vs spinel \u2014 same first-shell, different second-shell topology \u2014 must charge (currently fails: cost=0)",
          "op": "ge",
          "value": 0.5
        },
        {
          "assert": "cost",
          "description": "Bounded",
          "op": "le",
          "value": 100
        },
        {
          "assert": "cost_polyhedral",
          "description": "Polyhedral lens correctly distinguishes corner-sharing isolated tetrahedra from spinel's edge+corner-sharing framework",
          "op": "ge",
          "value": 1.0
        }
      ],
      "tags": [
        "core"
      ],
      "optimizer": "v1",
      "cost_function": "v1"
    },
    {
      "id": "ca2geo4_olivine_vs_mgal2o4_spinel",
      "type": "ged",
      "description": "Ca2GeO4 (Pnma \u2014 olivine structure with isolated GeO4 tetrahedra + Ca octahedra in HCP-O sublattice) vs MgAl2O4 spinel.  Companion to the chrysoberyl test: same Mg2SiO4-vs-MgAl2O4 failure mode.  Identical first-shell histograms (Ca CN=6=Al CN=6, Ge CN=4=Mg CN=4, O CN=4=O CN=4) \u2014 cohort comparison is perfectly balanced \u2014 but the framework topologies (olivine HCP-O isolated tetrahedra vs spinel CCP-O corner+edge-sharing) are textbook-different.  TopologyCost gives 0.0; polyhedral and bond-length lenses correctly flag the mismatch.  **Expected to FAIL** until second-shell signal is in the cost function.",
      "graph_a": "Ca2GeO4_mp-560647",
      "graph_b": "MgAl2O4_mp-3536",
      "cif_a": "Ca2GeO4_mp-560647.cif",
      "cif_b": "MgAl2O4_mp-3536.cif",
      "assertions": [
        {
          "assert": "cost",
          "description": "Olivine Ca2GeO4 vs cubic spinel \u2014 first-shell-isomorphic but second-shell-different (currently fails: cost=0)",
          "op": "ge",
          "value": 0.5
        },
        {
          "assert": "cost",
          "description": "Bounded",
          "op": "le",
          "value": 100
        },
        {
          "assert": "cost_polyhedral",
          "description": "Polyhedral lens distinguishes olivine's isolated tetrahedra from spinel's connected polyhedra",
          "op": "ge",
          "value": 1.0
        }
      ],
      "tags": [
        "core"
      ],
      "optimizer": "v1",
      "cost_function": "v1"
    },
    {
      "id": "srtio3_self_supercell_112",
      "type": "ged",
      "description": "SrTiO3 cubic Pm-3m unit cell (5 atoms) vs 1\u00d71\u00d72 supercell (10 atoms).  Same crystal structure, just doubled along one axis.  All cost lenses (topology, bond length, bond angle) must be exactly zero except polyhedral, where the v4 graph builder's `sharing_mode_hist` does not scale uniformly between unit-cell and supercell encodings \u2014 this is a known graph-builder artifact, not a genuine topological difference (NaCl supercell-self gives 0 across all four lenses, so the issue is SrTiO3-specific).  Tracking via a relaxed bound until that's addressed.",
      "graph_a": "SrTiO3_mp-5229",
      "graph_b": "SrTiO3_mp-5229_sup112",
      "cif_a": "SrTiO3_mp-5229.cif",
      "cif_b": "SrTiO3_mp-5229_sup112.cif",
      "assertions": [
        {
          "assert": "cost",
          "description": "Self-supercell: topology cost must be exactly zero",
          "op": "le",
          "value": 0.001
        },
        {
          "assert": "cost_bond_length",
          "description": "Self-supercell: bond lengths are identical",
          "op": "le",
          "value": 0.001
        },
        {
          "assert": "cost_bond_angle",
          "description": "Self-supercell: bond angles are identical",
          "op": "le",
          "value": 0.001
        },
        {
          "assert": "cost_polyhedral",
          "description": "Self-supercell: polyhedral cost is zero now that PolyhedralCost recomputes hist symmetrically (counting self-image edges as 2, matching cross-atom multiplicity)",
          "op": "le",
          "value": 0.001
        }
      ],
      "tags": [
        "cost_lens"
      ],
      "optimizer": "v1",
      "cost_function": "v1"
    },
